The day after, Schleicher sent a conservative with <span style="color: #7A3C00;">Nazi</span> connections to extract more details from [+ nsdap_leader +]. Unfortunately for Schleicher, the person he sent boasted that the army command stood ready to intervene if a new cabinet didn't conform to its wishes. The <span style="color: #7A3C00;">Nazi</span> leaders became fearful of a possible military putsch aimed at thwarting [+ nsdap_chancellor +]'s appointment.

Talk of a putsch quickly gave rise to a rapidly spreading, but unfounded rumor that Schleicher planned to depose Hindenburg and take the presidency for himself. Through Meissner and Papen, the news reached Hindenburg, giving a sense of urgency to replace Schleicher.

